abstract: U.S. President Donald Trump on Friday signed a proclamation increasing tariffs on derivative steel products by an additional 25 percent and boosting duties on derivative aluminum products by an additional 10 percent.
snippet: U.S. President Donald Trump on Friday signed a proclamation increasing tariffs on derivative steel products by an additional 25 percent and boosting duties on derivative aluminum products by an additional 10 percent.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — U.S. President Donald Trump on Friday signed a proclamation increasing tariffs on derivative steel products by an additional 25 percent and boosting duties on derivative aluminum products by an additional 10 percent.
headline_main: Trump Increases Tariffs on Derivative Steel, Aluminum Products From Some Countries
headline_print_headline: Trump Increases Tariffs on Derivative Steel, Aluminum Products From Some Countries

abstract: “Our primary interest right now is making sure that that person is protected,” the lawmaker said in October.
snippet: “Our primary interest right now is making sure that that person is protected,” the lawmaker said in October.
lead_paragraph: Patrick Philbin, another deputy White House counsel, used a portion of his time to suggest that Representative Adam B. Schiff initially wanted to hear testimony from the whistle-blower whose complaint helped force the Ukraine matter in to the open.
headline_main: Schiff was eager to hear whistle-blower testimony, defense team says.

abstract: The records examined by The New York Times — as the freeze on military aid was playing out — shows that some officials were pursuing the question of burden-sharing.
snippet: The records examined by The New York Times — as the freeze on military aid was playing out — shows that some officials were pursuing the question of burden-sharing.
lead_paragraph: President Trump’s lawyer, Pat A. Cipollone, opened the defense arguments by  saying that the Trump administration’s hold on military assistance to Ukraine — which was fighting a Russian-backed incursion on its eastern border — was driven by the president’s belief that other nations were not doing their share in supporting the former Soviet republic.
headline_main: Did ‘burden-sharing’ come up? Yes, it did.

abstract: “I’m not intimidated,” said Senator Richard Shelby, Republican of Alabama. “That was probably a little bit overboard.”
snippet: “I’m not intimidated,” said Senator Richard Shelby, Republican of Alabama. “That was probably a little bit overboard.”
lead_paragraph: Republicans continued to complain Saturday about Representative Adam B. Schiff’s “head on a pike” comment from the night before, with one saying it was so offensive because of its implication that senators were running scared and were intimidated by President Trump. That suggest did not go down well on the Senate floor.

abstract: The president’s lawyers insist that the ambassador to the European Union may have assumed there was a connection between security aid and the investigations but that he was wrong.
snippet: The president’s lawyers insist that the ambassador to the European Union may have assumed there was a connection between security aid and the investigations but that he was wrong.
lead_paragraph: “Not a single witness testified that the president himself said that there was any connection between any investigations and security assistance and a presidential meeting or anything else,” said Michael Purpura, one of the president’s lawyers.

headline_main: Gordon Sondland got it wrong, the president’s lawyers said.

abstract: President Donald Trump's lawyers opened his Senate impeachment defense Saturday with the false assertion that Democrats tried to shut the president's team out of the congressional inquiry that preceded the charges. Actually, Democrats invited Trump to participate and he declined.
snippet: President Donald Trump's lawyers opened his Senate impeachment defense Saturday with the false assertion that Democrats tried to shut the president's team out of the congressional inquiry that preceded the charges. Actually, Democrats invited Trum...
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Donald Trump's lawyers opened his Senate impeachment defense Saturday with the false assertion that Democrats tried to shut the president's team out of the congressional inquiry that preceded the charges. Actually, Democrats invited Trump to participate and he declined.
headline_main: AP FACT CHECK: Trump's Impeachment Defense and the Facts
headline_print_headline: AP FACT CHECK: Trump's Impeachment Defense and the Facts

abstract: One lawyer said the Ukrainians “did not even know that the security assistance was on hold until the end of August.” But Ukrainian officials knew about the suspension in assistance by late July.
snippet: One lawyer said the Ukrainians “did not even know that the security assistance was on hold until the end of August.” But Ukrainian officials knew about the suspension in assistance by late July.
lead_paragraph: A deputy White House counsel, Michael Purpura, correctly pointed out that President Volodymyr Zelensky of Ukraine has publicly denied that President Trump pressured him. But Gordon D. Sondland, the American ambassador to the European Union, testified that he told Mr. Zelensky’s top advisers of the demand by Mr. Trump to announce investigations. Veteran diplomats say that Mr. Zelensky could not be expected to publicly criticize Mr. Trump when he so badly needs the United States’s support.

headline_main: The president’s lawyers omit a few facts about Ukraine’s dealings.

abstract: The strategy reminds senators of how much repetition there was in the House managers’ case and may earn some good will from the senators.
snippet: The strategy reminds senators of how much repetition there was in the House managers’ case and may earn some good will from the senators.
lead_paragraph: President Trump’s lawyers appear to have noticed how restless senators got during the more than 21 hours of arguments by the House Democratic managers over three days.
headline_main: White House jabs at the length of the House managers’ case.

abstract: Jay Sekulow accused the House Democratic managers of having “tried once again to re-litigate the Mueller case.”
snippet: Jay Sekulow accused the House Democratic managers of having “tried once again to re-litigate the Mueller case.”
lead_paragraph: President Trump’s defense lawyers echoed one of their client’s frequent lines of attack as they began their arguments on Saturday: that Democrats have been out to get him since long before Ukraine was a household word.

headline_main: Lawyers zero in on the Mueller inquiry.

abstract: “They’re asking you to tear up all of the ballots all across the country on your own initiative, take that decision away from the American people,” the White House counsel said of the House managers.
snippet: “They’re asking you to tear up all of the ballots all across the country on your own initiative, take that decision away from the American people,” the White House counsel said of the House managers.
lead_paragraph: As the trial moved into a new phase after three days of arguments by the House managers prosecuting President Trump for high crimes and misdemeanors, the president’s lawyers presented the senators a radically different view of the facts and the Constitution, seeking to turn the Democrats’ charges back on them while denouncing the whole process as illegitimate.
headline_main: Trump’s team mounts its defense as it turns Democrats’ charges back on them.
